1
00:00:00,318 --> 00:00:29,126
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambho Tassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambho Tassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambho Tassa Homage to the Buddha, the Blessed, Noble and Fully Self-Enlightened.

2
00:00:31,199 --> 00:00:37,088
So the word tonight is Anusaya, A-N-U-S-A-Y-A.

3
00:00:38,070 --> 00:00:50,329
And the translation in the Pali text dictionary is a bent, a proclivity, latent tendency and predisposition.

4
00:00:50,770 --> 00:00:54,235
And the one that really interests me is this translation of latent tendency.

5
00:00:54,515 --> 00:00:55,737
But we'll come to that in a minute.

6
00:00:58,435 --> 00:01:01,438
In the early scriptures, the Buddha only talks about anusaya.

7
00:01:01,457 --> 00:01:02,499
He doesn't actually say what they are.

8
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:05,022
It's just latent tendencies.

9
00:01:05,182 --> 00:01:07,103
We've all got latent tendencies.

10
00:01:07,123 --> 00:01:18,936
But later on, in the scriptures, a different level of the scriptures, perhaps as his teaching matures, things are added to this latent tendency.

11
00:01:19,055 --> 00:01:21,938
Pride, doubt, ignorance, lust, and so on.

12
00:01:22,920 --> 00:01:28,424
And in the end, in the Abhidhamma, they list it as seven.

13
00:01:28,489 --> 00:01:34,917
So the first one, well, the way they list it is sensual lust.

14
00:01:35,778 --> 00:01:41,944
I think it's probably better, even though it says karma roga, it does mean body lust, but anyway.

15
00:01:42,323 --> 00:01:47,409
Attachment to existence, aversion, conceit, wrong views, doubt, and ignorance.

16
00:01:47,750 --> 00:01:51,433
So none of them have come as a big surprise, eh?

17
00:01:51,453 --> 00:01:54,496
Now, to try and make sense of this list...

18
00:01:55,135 --> 00:02:00,921
It seems to me that you've got to just turn the order around a bit for some reason.

19
00:02:02,063 --> 00:02:22,948
If we take ignorance as a basic platform, as a latent tendency in the sense of not knowing, then you immediately enter into the delusion on the one side of wrong views and on the other side of self, which expresses itself as conceit.

20
00:02:23,722 --> 00:02:27,325
So it's, I have this view, I'm right and everybody else is wrong.

21
00:02:28,086 --> 00:02:29,568
That's your basic position.

22
00:02:30,710 --> 00:02:39,098
And from there, you fork into three, which relates to the way that the self relates to the world.

23
00:02:39,520 --> 00:02:41,681
Sensual pleasure and becoming.

24
00:02:42,143 --> 00:02:46,067
So that's to do with greed and acquisitiveness.

25
00:02:46,520 --> 00:02:50,223
Then you've got the aversion, so that's the negative side, not wanting.

26
00:02:50,805 --> 00:02:56,390
And then the doubt, which is the befuddlement that comes because of this basic ignorance.

27
00:02:57,512 --> 00:03:00,615
So that's your sort of latent dispositions.

28
00:03:01,997 --> 00:03:09,625
Now, these latent dispositions, what

29
00:03:10,431 --> 00:03:21,885
It can't be the fact that, at least as I understand it, the Buddha didn't teach that we had some sort of store memory that you pick books off, like a library or something.

30
00:03:22,806 --> 00:03:32,418
It's more like, and that's why I like this word, latent tendency, some sort of predisposition, but it doesn't actually have any actuality.

31
00:03:33,058 --> 00:03:35,882
And I think one of the best,

32
00:03:36,587 --> 00:04:02,139
analogies is of a computer really because if you take metaphor to a logical end it's normally a sign of madness so it only works at certain levels you know so when we shut the computer down and unplug it and all that it's dead it's not but we know it's got this tremendous latent ability and then when you plug it in

33
00:04:02,456 --> 00:04:06,145
You can connect to the whole worldwide web, for heaven's sake.

34
00:04:06,164 --> 00:04:07,407
I mean, that's the potential of it.

35
00:04:07,508 --> 00:04:11,957
But when it's unplugged, it remains there just as purely latent.

36
00:04:11,978 --> 00:04:21,579
So all these conditionings, see the other word it uses, predisposition, and that links us with these sankaras, these volitional conditionings.

37
00:04:22,235 --> 00:04:28,105
So they're lying there in wait, you might say, but in this sort of non-existent form.

38
00:04:29,908 --> 00:04:32,312
But it's there within the psychic system, you could say.

39
00:04:32,954 --> 00:04:36,699
So something happens and they're there to be pulled out.

40
00:04:37,220 --> 00:04:46,838
And that I think, you know, connects rather nicely with our modern psychology about subliminal stuff and subconscious stuff.

41
00:04:46,898 --> 00:04:54,932
Although you do get the feeling from Freudian stuff and all that, that's already there as it were.

42
00:04:54,992 --> 00:04:57,557
It's in a sort of stored memory.

43
00:04:58,245 --> 00:05:06,660
But I think this is slightly more subtle in the sense that every moment comes to an end completely.

44
00:05:06,699 --> 00:05:08,603
It's a radical impermanence.

45
00:05:09,103 --> 00:05:13,992
So you can't hold anything, and yet there's the potential.

46
00:05:14,232 --> 00:05:16,997
So it's one of these little mysteries, really.

47
00:05:19,896 --> 00:05:32,052
So really, without going into all these different things more deeply, those are your seven latent tendencies.

48
00:05:32,293 --> 00:05:38,461
Ignorance, the not knowing, which forks into this I am conceit with wrong view.

49
00:05:38,502 --> 00:05:47,793
And that again forks into these three avenues, the sensual pleasure, the becoming,

50
00:05:48,988 --> 00:05:50,550
There's always that.

51
00:05:50,610 --> 00:05:52,713
There's the bhāvatanda.

52
00:05:53,435 --> 00:06:07,052
When he describes dukkha as such, it's attachment to pleasure, the desire to keep becoming, becoming a self, in other words, keep being reborn as me.

53
00:06:08,192 --> 00:06:12,577
And the opposite is vibhāva, which is the desire to put an end to that.

54
00:06:13,418 --> 00:06:17,865
And that comes into the other fork, the aversion, not wanting.

55
00:06:18,098 --> 00:06:23,122
It comes in obvious forms of not wanting something and not wanting to live.

56
00:06:24,463 --> 00:06:35,415
And the third one is this doubt which comes from befuddlement, which comes from confusion that arises out of this self.

57
00:06:36,375 --> 00:06:38,898
So those are your seven anusaya.

58
00:06:39,879 --> 00:06:45,625
And in a sense, if you think about it, that is the platform

59
00:06:46,245 --> 00:06:48,730
out of which we then create the world.

60
00:06:48,949 --> 00:06:52,276
We create these sankharas, create these volitional conditionings.

61
00:06:52,295 --> 00:06:55,060
So underneath it, there is that not knowing.

62
00:06:55,240 --> 00:07:08,822
It's creating a certain disposition, which then manifests a disposition of I am with a view, then manifests as this more obvious psychological thing of wanting, not wanting, being confused.

63
00:07:09,583 --> 00:07:12,608
And then as something happens to us in daily life,

64
00:07:13,279 --> 00:07:20,108
It picks up on one of these and then you suddenly find yourself being greedy or being hateful or being confused.

65
00:07:20,949 --> 00:07:22,773
And that's basically, I think, how it is.

66
00:07:23,312 --> 00:07:35,369
So these anusaya, you could look at them as the potential which has been created from past actions that we call these sankaras, volitional conditioning.

67
00:07:35,709 --> 00:07:42,678
So these volitional conditionings become, sink, as it were, into this level of sheer potential.

68
00:07:43,839 --> 00:07:45,682
And I think that's what the Buddha is saying.

69
00:07:50,870 --> 00:08:02,526
And the final thing is that until these anusaya are actually eradicated from the system, there's no way our unwholesome actions can stop.

70
00:08:04,988 --> 00:08:12,379
And the only way you can undermine them is through insight, which breaks the delusion.

71
00:08:12,882 --> 00:08:27,860
That's why in dependent origination the real break is at that point of ignorance.

72
00:08:27,880 --> 00:08:30,904
So that brings to an end my little homily on the Anusaya.

73
00:08:31,225 --> 00:08:33,869
I can only hope it has been of some benefit.

74
00:08:34,669 --> 00:08:40,576
May you be liberated from all your Anusaya sooner rather than later.

